{{#demo-css}}
<h3 class="title"><b>Component</b>::mini-datetime</h3>
<desc>A lightweight component for displaying both date and time in a relatively small screen real estate.</desc>

<h3>Basic Example</h3>

<row>
  <widget class="{{if containerSize 'wide'}}">
    {{mini-datetime
      value='2015-05-04 14:45:00'
      size=fontSize
      font=fontFamily
    }}
  </widget>
  <code>
    {{display-component componentName='mini-datetime'
      value='2015-05-04 14:45:00'
      size=fontSize
      font=fontFamily
    }}
  </code>
  <description>
    <p>
      This example takes a timedate string and then paints it into the space the container provides
      using CSS flexbox as the underlying layout.
    </p>
    <p>
      Using the button below allows you to toggle between two container sizes to provide a view on how
      the component fills in the available space.
    </p>
    container size: {{ui-toggle-button on='wide' off='narrow' value=containerSize}}
  </description>
</row>

<row>
  <p>
    Two other style properties that can be passed to the component are font <i>size</i> and <i>family</i>.
    Rather than actually setting the <prop>style</prop> on the various DIV's we instead use a set of CSS
    classes which can be easily overriden by the user and exposed to lower risk of XSS attacks.
  </p>
</row>
<row>
  <column>
    Try adjusting the two properties and then inspect the HTML with your debugger.
    You will see that the <prop>size</prop> parameter translates into a css property
    of <css>.size-XXX</css> and <css>.font-YYY</css> respectively.
  </column>
  <column>
    size: {{radio-buttons buttons='tiny,small,default,large,huge' value=fontSize defaultValue='normal' size='small'}}<br/>
    family: {{radio-buttons buttons='inherit,fantasy,monospace,cursive,serif,sans-serif' value=fontFamily defaultValue='inherit' size='small'}}<br/>
  </column>
</row>


<h3 >Start, Stop, and Duration</h3>
<row>
  <widget class="{{if containerSize 'wide'}}">
    {{mini-datetime
      startTime='2015-05-04 13:34:00'
      duration=d1
      size=fontSize
      font=fontFamily
      ampm=ampm
      cursor=cursorString
      showDuration=showDuration
    }}
  </widget>
  <code>
    {{display-component componentName='mini-datetime'
      startTime='2015-05-04 13:34:00'
      duration=d1
      size=fontSize
      font=fontFamily
      ampm=ampm
      cursor=cursorString
      showDuration=showDuration
    }}
  </code>
  <description>
   <div class="row">
     <div class="col-xs-4">Ending Style:</div>
     <div class="col-xs-8">{{radio-buttons buttons='stop time:::null,duration:::true' value=showDuration size='small' stretch=true defaultValue=true}}</div>
   </div>
   <div class="row">
     <div class="col-xs-4">Duration:</div>
     <div class="col-xs-8">{{radio-buttons buttons='0:::0,30:::30,60:::60,90:::90' value=d1 size='small' stretch=true}}</div>
   </div>
   <div class="row">
      <div class="col-xs-5">
        Time Format<br/>
      {{ui-toggle-button off='24hr time' on='am/pm' value=ampm size='small'}}<br/>
      </div>
      <div class="col-xs-7">
        Cursor<br/>
        {{ui-toggle-button off='default' on='not-allowed' value=cursor size='small'}}<br/>
      </div>
    </div>

  </description>
</row>

<desc>
  In the example above we've added another property "stopTime" which allows another <em>datetime</em> object to be included as the "stop time". Another similar alternative would be to instead specify the
  <code>duration</code> property which is the number minutes which is really just another way of providing the
  same information but having both input formats helps to provide a more flexible API surface for two very common
  ways of expressing this kind of information.
</desc>
<desc>
  In addition to providing two interfaces, the user interface can also be asked to display the secondary date information as a <em>duration</em> or a concluding <em>time</em>. The components attempts to be smart by mimicking the input format to the user interface for intra-day durations. For any multi-day durations the
  component switches to <em>duration </em> mode.
</desc>

<h3>Data Down, Actions Up</h3>
<row>
  <widget class="{{if containerSize 'wide'}}">
    {{mini-datetime
      value='2015-05-04 13:34:00'
      duration=duration
      size=fontSize
      font=fontFamily
      ampm=ampm
      showDuration=showDuration
      disabled=disabled
      actionSupport=actionSupport
      numDateChoices=numDateChoices
    }}
  </widget>
  <code>
    {{display-component componentName='mini-datetime'
      value='2015-05-04 13:34:00'
      duration=duration
      size=fontSize
      font=fontFamily
      ampm=ampm
      showDuration=showDuration
      disabled=disabled
      actionSupport=actionSupport
      numDateChoices=numDateChoices
    }}
  </code>
  <description>
    Disabling<br/>
    {{ui-toggle-button off='enabled' on='disabled' value=disabled}}<br/>
    Action Support<br/>
    {{ui-toggle-button off='off' on='on' value=actionSupport defaultValue=false}}<br/>
    # of Date Choices<br/>
    {{radio-buttons buttons='4,5,6' value=numDateChoices}}<br/>
  </description>
</row>

